It’s nice in the sense that sharing this OC art with close friends, I realize their comments mean the most to me and their validation, because they are invested in something that’s specifically mine and that does feel really good, even if twitter is more lonely for me now
I feel like extremely small fandoms also function just about the same. Does anyone else feel this way?

they only really care if your a professional career artist who won the twitter lottery and have over 10k followers — so in a way, it’s interesting, because I feel like there is nothing to lose and nothing to gain, and therefore my artistic journey is both freed but isolating

So i think in that enviornment, it’s nearly impossible to not compare yourself to other content creators even if you strive for your own happiness in your creation. The thing with oc’s is that people in fandom don’t really care about oc’s for the most part —

It’s lonely being into your own oc’s but I also find that there’s a plus side to not having to worry about other content creators, which I think inevitably happens when you wanna grow as an artist and your only means of validation are through twitter stats and comments

I think getting into my own oc’s was really good for me bc I think my relationship with fandom community, while having a plethora of fun collab and new friends to make, always negatively impacts my relationship with my own art in various aspects

@plutosyndrome It’s weird being 27 and being obsessed with art since like 5 years old, bc i grew up in an age with cheap offbrand  hand me down bamboo tablets and a deviantart at a desktop 3 other siblings fought over LOL— sketchbooks were absolutely the way to go for me

Im glad i did it so it felt like i was catching up with the rest of the world (being so engulfed by fandom social media) but also there was a hole missing in my heart that whole time in some weird way

I mainly worked in traditional throughout all of my teen and early twenties years and i feel like once i hit 22-23 i made this massive shove into strictly only working in digital and i feel i lost something in myself through doing that, as far as personal experience goes

Anyway not to get on a soap box here but i totally recommend mixing up your craft or taking on some sorta traditional medium outside of digital work, not so you can necessarily experience what im experiencing but bc it can feel different for people and can be enlightening!!
